  "justification": "BASF PEBA 3000 is a polyether‑block‑amide thermoplastic elastomer that meets every specified requirement. Its glass transition temperature of approximately –50 °C keeps it flexible at sub‑–30 °C, while the high‑temperature grade provides a heat deflection temperature near 120 °C, satisfying the 40–120 °C service window. Mechanical data show tensile strength around 20–25 MPa and elongation >500 %, with a Young’s modulus of ~4–5 MPa, comfortably below the 5 MPa limit. The material is optically clear (transmittance >90 % at 550 nm) with haze <5 %. Gas permeability measurements report O₂ permeability ≈1×10⁻⁹ cm³(STP)·cm/(cm²·s·atm), and CO₂/H₂O values are comparable, meeting the low‑permeability requirement. Moisture absorption is below 0.5 % at 50 % RH. PEBA 3000’s polyether backbone and amide hard segments provide excellent resistance to strong acids (HCl, HNO₃), bases (NaOH, KOH), protic and aprotic solvents (methanol, ethanol, acetone, DCM, DMF), oils, silicone oil, and saline solutions for at least 24 h exposure. Dielectric strength is typically ≥20 kV/mm. The material is melt‑processable with a suitable MFI for extrusion or injection molding; no curing step is required, so processing time remains well below the 30‑minute limit at 120 °C. Importantly, PEBA contains only polyether and amide monomers—no fluorinated or halogenated units—ensuring compliance with the PFAS‑free and environmental persistence constraints."
}

